27. Final provisions
27.1 This Treaty is a full agreement between the Parties on the subject matter of this Treaty. This Treaty supersedes all previous agreements of the Parties on the subject matter of this Treaty.
27.2 This Treaty may be amended only in writing, in ascending numbered appendices. A complete consensus of the parties' expressions of will is needed to amend this Treaty. A response containing an amendment or deviation from the original proposal that does not materially alter the terms of such a proposal is not the adoption of a proposal.
27.3 This Treaty is governed by Czech law. Disputes under this Treaty are decided by the Municipal Court in Prague.
27.4. If one of the Parties does not exercise its rights under this Treaty or exercises such rights belatedly, this does not mean that the Party has waived such rights. Each Party may exercise its rights repeatedly, both in its entirety and in part. The rights provided for in this Treaty may be exercised in parallel. The exercise of rights under this Treaty shall not preclude any right arising from legislation.
27.5 If a court or public authority decides that a provision of this Treaty is invalid or ineffective, the other provisions of this Treaty, and this Treaty as a whole, shall remain in force and effect. The Parties shall replace an invalid or ineffective provision with a valid and effective provision in such a way as to best achieve the intended economic, legal and commercial purposes of the invalid or ineffective provision.
