Annex No 6 / Project Management Methodology
1. Project charter
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and mode of communication between the parties in order to fulfil the subject matter of the Treaty so that the execution of the work or the provision of services is in accordance with the Treaty and this Project Management Methodology. For those involved in the performance of a work or the provision of services, the Project Charter makes available the parts of the Treaty necessary to fulfil its object. The project charter identifies the occupation of the project's organisational structure, the method of communication, the control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal on which all documentation related to the execution of the work or the provision of services is archived. The project charter will be developed by the project manager and approved by the initial Steering commitee meeting.
2. Project Organizational Structure
2.1 The project's organisational components are (1) the Project Steering Committee (SCP) and (2) Project Leadership (PCP) and (3) the work teams. SCP and PVP are the project's permanent organisational units. The work teams are the project's temporary organisational units.
3. Steering committee
3.1 Powers of the SCP / Steering committee of the project in particular:
3.1.1 Approves the Project Charter; and
3.1.2 addresses escalated issues that have not been resolved at the PVP level; and
3.1.3 addresses issues with an impact on the scope of the work performed or the services provided; and beyond
3.1.4 addresses issues related to delivery schedules; and beyond
3.1.5 addresses issues related to the remuneration or structure of remuneration for services rendered or work performed; and
3.1.6 accepts individual supplies, services, parts of a work or a work as a whole; and beyond
3.2 Members of the SCP / For the Orderer are members of the SCP (1) the project sponsor for business and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the project leader. For the Zhotovitele, the SCP members are (1) management representatives and (2) project leaders.
3.3 The SCP/SCP meetings shall meet at least once a quarter. The exact days on which the SCP regularly sits will be determined by the Project Manager in the Project Charter. The SCP shall always meet when assessing a significant milestone in the delivery schedule (e.g. commencement or termination of the acceptance procedure). The SCP shall meet whenever a project leader invites the SCP to a meeting. The SCP sits at the head office of the Client.
3.4. SCP meeting agenda / SCP meeting agenda and papers to be discussed shall be delivered to the SCP members by the Project Manager on behalf of the contractor, at least 3 working days before the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP shall always discuss a report on the status of the project and draft minutes relating to the acceptance of a supply, service or work.
3.5. Right to invite experts and advisors / If a Party deems it necessary, it shall have the right to invite experts or advisors to the SCP's meetings, but shall notify the other Party in advance, stating the reasons why the presence of experts or advisors at the SCP's meetings is expedient.
3.6 Voting / After discussing each item on the agenda, SCP members shall vote on the proposal submitted to the relevant item on the agenda. Each member of the SCP shall have one vote.
3.7 Decisions of the SCP affecting the contractual terms / Where the decision of the SCP relates to the contractual terms under which a work is performed or services provided, in particular where the decision of the SCP affects the remuneration for which the work is performed or services provided, the Client shall, without undue delay after taking such a decision, prepare an addendum to the contract in question.
3.8. Minutes / From the SCP meeting, the project manager draws up a minutes on behalf of the Orderer, which he delivers to the project manager on behalf of the Zhotovitele.
4. Project management
4.1 PVP/Project management powers in particular:
4.1.1 checks all outputs of the various stages of the execution of a work or the provision of services; and
4.1.2 evaluates and refines the delivery schedule and the progress of works in the execution of works or provision of services; and
4.1.3 discusses changes that do not affect the text of the Treaty; and
4.1.4 manages the interaction between the Entitlement and the Entity; and beyond
4.1.5 manages the risks and remedies associated with the performance of a work or the provision of services; and
4.1.6 escalates to the SCP meeting.
4.2 Members of the PVP / For the Orderer are members of the PVP (1) the project leader and (2) the main business analyst and (3) the application architect. For Zhotovitele, the members of PVP (1) are the project leader and (2) the chief analyst and (3) the chief architect.
4.3 The SCP/PVP meets once a week, at the head office of the Orderer or in the form of remote communication.
4.4 The agenda of the PVP meeting and the background / The agenda of the PVP meeting and the background to be discussed will be delivered to the PVP members by the Project Manager under the Zhotovitele, at least 1 working day before the PVP meeting. At its meeting, the PVP always discusses:
4.4.1 Performing Open Tasks from Previous PVPs; and
4.4.2 Progress in the execution of a work or provision of services; and
4.4.3 delivering and updating work schedules; and
4.4.4 identified problems and how to address them; and
4.4.5 roadmap; and
4.4.6 risks associated with the performance of a work or the provision of services; and
4.4.7 Evaluation and Other Requirements for Contributor Interoperability; and
4.4.8 status and severity of unresolved defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 Change Requirements; and
4.5 Right to invite experts and advisers / Where their presence is expedient for the efficient conduct of negotiations, both parties have the right to invite experts and advisers, or project team members, to the PCA meetings.
4.6 Entry / From the PVP meeting, the Project Manager draws up the entry for the Orderer, which he delivers to the Project Manager for the Zhotovitele.
5. Work Teams
5.1. Work Teams/Work Teams consist of workers from the Order or the Zhotovitele and, where appropriate, workers from third parties. In particular, the work teams (1) carry out specific parts of the work or the services provided and (2) provide the know-how needed to perform the work or provide the services, and (3) provide factual and expert input for further decision-making.
5.2 Roles in working teams / Role casting is always adapted to the current stage of performance of a work or provision of services. On the Orderer side, the members of the work team are:
5.2.1 Business area analysts
5.2.2 Garant / key user of the area/areas
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the Zhotovitele side, the members of the work team are:
5.2.4 Principal consultant/analyst - architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/Analyst
5.2.6 Technical infrastructure specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, Trainer
5.2.9 Operating and installation specialist
6. The Project Charter determines a complete overview of the casting of individual project roles and their communication matrix.Rules of communication between each other
6.1 In particular, the project manager manages communication/communication in the project. Communication is always done matter-of-factly, with the aim of solving individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, managed, project team communication includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project meetings (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops, …)
6.1.2 Acceptance and handover procedures
6.1.3 Transfer and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Recording of change requirements
6.1.5 Recording of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - agenda and background / Schedule and list of tasks from project meetings are always updated at the next meeting. The documents that will be the subject of the project meeting will be sent by the project manager to the participants in the meeting in advance, depending on the subject matter. The supporting documents are recorded and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Project meeting minutes / For each project meeting, the project manager of the project will draw up a written minutes which will be delivered to the project manager of the Zhotovitele the following working day after the project meeting.
6.4 Amendments and additions to the Project Meeting Minutes / Amendments and additions to the Project Meeting Minutes shall be made by the participants within 2 working days of the date of receipt of the minutes. Negotiations on modifications and additions to the minutes are managed by the project manager. Editing and supplementing the minutes is no place to hold a discussion. Once the modifications and additions have been incorporated, the project manager of the Order closes the minutes of the project meeting and stores them on the project portal. The deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting may be changed by the project manager by agreement. If any time limit to comment on the minutes of a project meeting expires without comments from the participants in the meeting, the minutes shall be deemed approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and registration of risks / During the execution of a work or the provision of services, all interested parties identify and subsequently manage in a documented manner risks which may affect the quality of the outputs or the timing for the execution of the work or the provision of services. The risks are registered by the project manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Risk discussion at the PVP/Risk assessment meeting is a mandatory agenda item for each PVP meeting. The PVP meeting sets out measures to eliminate or minimise the risks.
7.3 Escalation / If there is a disagreement or if a risk of severity affecting the contractual arrangement or schedule or reward is identified, such a risk will escalate to the PVP at the SCP meeting.
8. Quality management
8.1 The basic tool for managing the quality of project outputs is the acceptance procedure. The following are subject to quality verification:
8.1.1 Checking the completeness of the subject matter of the work or the provision of services in order to fulfil the purpose of the contract
8.1.2 Evaluation and settlement of observations, defects and incidents to fulfil the purpose of the contract
8.1.3 Check that documentation is up to date and complete
