Annex 3
DETAILED BYT CORRECTIONS
1. Minor repairs are considered to be repairs to a dwelling and its interior furnishings if the furnishings are part of the dwelling and are owned by the landlord, depending on the material definition or the amount of the expense.
2. Depending on the material definition, the following corrections and replacements are considered minor repairs:
a. repairs to individual upper floors, repairs to floor coverings and threshold and rail replacements,
Repairs to individual parts of windows and doors and their components, and changes to locks, fittings, cranks, blinds and blinds;
c. exchanges of electrical terminal equipment and distribution devices, in particular switches, sockets, circuit breakers, bell, domestic telephones, data network outlets, analogue and digital television signals, and exchanges of light sources in lighting bodies;
d. replacement of shut-off valves for gas distribution, except for the main housing closure;
e. repairs of sealing fittings on water mains, siphon exchanges and fat traps,
f. repairs of heating indicators and repairs and certification of residential hot and cold water meters.
3. Furthermore, minor repairs include repairs to water spouts, odour seals, vapour hoods, digesters, mixing batteries, showers, water heaters, bidets, washbasins, tubs, drains, sinks, flushes, kitchen stoves, baking ovens, cookers, infrared lights, kitchen cabinets, built-in and built-in cabinets.
For heating installations, repairs to solid fuel stoves, gas and electricity, boilers of space heating on solid, liquid and gaseous fuels, including closing and regulating fittings and control thermostats of space heating are considered minor repairs; however, repairs to radiators and central heating distribution systems are not considered to be minor repairs.
4. Exchanges of small parts of articles referred to in the preceding paragraphs shall also be considered minor repairs.
5. Depending on the amount of the load, other repairs to the flat and its furnishings and the replacement of components of the individual items of this equipment not mentioned in paragraphs 2 and 3 shall be considered minor repairs if the cost per repair does not exceed CZK 500.
Where several related and time-related corrections are made to the same case, the sum of the related repair costs is decisive.
Transport and other repair costs, if included in the tax document proving the repair, are not included in the cost of that repair, but are part of the annual limit below.
6. The sum of the costs of the minor repairs referred to in paragraphs 2 to 5 may not exceed CZK 70 per square metre of floor space per calendar year of the flat, including transport costs and other costs associated with the repair, if indicated in the tax document proving the repair.
7. For the purposes of this Annex, the floor area of a dwelling shall be the sum of the floor areas of the dwelling and its accessories, even outside the dwelling, if used exclusively by the tenant of the dwelling; the floor area of non-rooms cellars and the floor area of balconies, loggias and terraces shall count for only one half.
COSTS CONCERNED WITH THE CURRENT BYT MAINTENANCE
The costs associated with the normal upkeep of a flat are the costs of maintaining and cleaning the flat, which are usually carried out with prolonged use of the flat.
These include regular inspections and cleaning of the items listed above (gas hobs, etc.), painting, including repairing plasters, wallpapering and cleaning floors, including floor coverings, wall coverings, cleaning of littered waste up to vertical wiring and interior paint.
The soldiers are rehearsing, pull down the curtains. China sets up celebrations at the site of the massacre
The army rehearsed the parade during recent weekends. Shops in central Beijing had to close and residents near the square were ordered to close their curtains. Military trucks rolled down the deserted streets toward the plaza, and fighter jets circled in the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters they were proud that their country would display its military might. But one woman said it was hard to deny that celebrations would make other states uneasy.
She was apparently referring to Taiwan, which China claims and where elections are coming up. But they may also be worried in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, in which thousands of people have repeatedly demonstrated against the Chinese-appointed administrator.
Celebrations are also being prepared outside Beijing. The southern Chinese port of Xianmen had already put on a special light show on Thursday night. Siamen is across from island Taiwan and is one of China's ten most innovative cities.
The list of forbidden items is growing ahead of the anniversary. It already has drones, balloons, dragons, alcohol, radios and devices using radio waves, the Guardian pointed out. He added that China's popular social network Weibo was deleting "damaging political information."
"It's another milestone, another opportunity to show that the Chinese Communist Party is staying (at the oar) despite all the predictions," said historian Maura Cunningham, who covers China. "It is a moment when the party can demonstrate order, control and power," she added.
The People's Republic of China was established in 1949 when the Communists, led by Mao Zedong, won the battle with Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists, who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of the 1960s, China underwent a disastrous communist experiment in the form of the so-called Cultural Revolution. In June 1989, the regime in Tiananmen Square massacred thousands of pro-democracy protesters, both students and workers, with tanks.
Since the late 1970s, China has increasingly taken on elements of the capitalist economy. According to critics, it is now a mixture of the worst of communism (one-party monopoly and persecution of the opposition) and (Dickensian) capitalism (worker exploitation).
