b. damaging an apartment or house in a serious or irreparable way;
c. if it causes otherwise serious damage or inconvenience to the landlord or persons living in the house; or
d. if he improperly uses the apartment in any other way or for a purpose than that agreed upon.
If the landlord does not state in the notice what he considers to be a particularly serious breach of the tenant's obligations, or if he does not, before the notice is served, call upon the tenant to put an end to his wrongful conduct within a reasonable time or to put an end to the wrongful situation, the notice shall be disregarded.
The tenant is obliged to give the apartment to the landlord on the day the tenancy ends.
The flat is surrendered if the landlord receives the keys and otherwise there is nothing to prevent him from accessing and using the flat.
If the tenant leaves the apartment in such a way that the tenancy can be deemed to have ended without any doubt, the apartment shall be deemed to have been surrendered immediately.
The tenant is obliged to surrender the flat in the condition in which he took it, notwithstanding the normal wear and tear of normal use and the defects which the landlord is obliged to eliminate.
The tenant is obliged to remove the changes he has made to the apartment with the landlord's consent if the parties have agreed to restore the apartment to its original state at the end of the tenancy.
The tenant is required to remove the changes he has made to the apartment without the landlord's consent, unless the landlord informs the tenant that he does not ask for the changes to be removed; nevertheless, the tenant cannot claim compensation even if the changes increase the value of the home.
The landlord may claim compensation in the amount of the reduction in the value of the dwelling due to changes made by the tenant without the landlord's consent.
Fittings and objects fixed in the walls, floor and ceiling of a dwelling which cannot be removed without undue depreciation of value or damage to the dwelling or house are transferred by attachment or insertion into the ownership of the owner of the dwelling.
The tenant has the right to demand that the landlord settle with him without undue delay; this is not true of what the tenant has done without the landlord's consent.
Compensation is due no later than the end date of the lease.
The landlord has the right to compensation in the amount of the agreed rent if the tenant does not give the apartment to the landlord on the expiry date until the day the tenant actually gives the apartment to the landlord.
If an item is left in an apartment that can be considered to belong to the tenant or a member of his household, the landlord takes care of the item for the benefit of the tenant and on his behalf.
If the tenant does not take over the item without undue delay, the landlord shall have the right to sell the item in an appropriate manner on his behalf, after giving an additional reasonable period of time to take it over.
This shall not apply if the item is one which the tenant or a member of his household has apparently abandoned.
The lessee may terminate the lease if the circumstances on which the parties appear to have relied at the inception of the obligation under the lease change to such an extent that the lessee cannot reasonably be required to continue the lease.
If the tenant dies, the contract is governed by section 2279 et seq. of the Civil Code.
VIII. Final provisions
This contract was drawn up in two copies, each of the contracting parties receiving a copy each.
